{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018K9VmBXWXT1jiDkKMC8rjd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the issue clearly. The StatefulSet:\n1. Only mounts `es-config` (elasticsearch.yml) and `es-certs` (TLS certs)\n2. Does NOT mount any file realm secrets (`es-file-realm-aggregate` or `user-provided-file-realm`)\n3. The `elasticsearch.yml` does not configure a file realm with custom paths\n\nThe precondition created two secrets:\n- `es-file-realm-aggregate` - contains `ops-user` with `superuser` role\n- `user-provided-file-realm` - contains `report-user` with `viewer` role\n\nBut neither secret is mounted into the pods, and the default file realm paths (`/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/users` and `//usr/share/elasticsearch/config/users_roles`) don't contain these users, so neither can authenticate. I need to check what the precondition actually does with the `ops-user` since it might be configured differently than I'm assuming.\n\nLooking at the precondition more carefully, the curl check for `ops-user` runs up to 60 times but exits successfully regardless of whether authentication actually works, so `ops-user` might not be authenticating either. The task description says to restore access for the new `report-user` without breaking existing users, which implies `ops-user` is currently working. Let me verify what's actually happening with both users and the `elastic` superuser.\n\nThe real problem is that neither the `es-file-realm-aggregate` secret containing `ops-user` nor the `user-provided-file-realm` secret containing `report-user` are mounted into the container, so neither realm is accessible to Elasticsearch even though they're defined in the configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1737,"cache_read_input_tokens":33519,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"e